title: 10 Delicious Dip Recipes, Ranked In Order Of How Terrible They Are For You

organizations.name: shutterstock & joyful healthy eats/krista rollins roasted garlic white bean

text:
Black pepper, fresh cilantro as needed 
How to Make It: 
Drizzle jalapeno with olive oil and roast in the oven at 375 until slightly blackened. Blend yogurt, spices, jalapeno, avocado, lime juice and cilantro in a blender until smooth. Serve with one half cup of cucumbers and ten carrot sticks. (Makes 1 large serving) 2/10 Shutterstock & Culinary Hill/Meggan Hill BLACK BEAN SALSA 
The best thing about this fresh black bean salsa is its versatility. Toss it together with any kind of bell pepper, bean, or onion—and if you want to add a nice healthy fat, you can throw in some avocado, too. Looking for a bit of a kick? Add some jalapeno or Tabasco to it. You’ll get a good dose of fiber from the vegetables and some protein from the beans. 
(Find the full recipe here .) 3/10 Shutterstock & Joyful Healthy Eats/Krista Rollins ROASTED GARLIC WHITE BEAN HUMMUS 
The white bean base of this hummus makes it stand out from its traditional chickpea counterparts. Plus, the beans deliver a punch of protein and the combination of garlic, cumin, paprika, and olive oil will make this snack taste like you tried way harder than you did. 
(Find the full recipe here .) 4/10 Shutterstock & Inspired Taste/Adam Gallagher HOMEMADE GUACAMOLE 
Everyone loves homemade guacamole for a reason: It’s fresh, creamy, and super simple to make. A sprinkle of cumin enhances the rest of the flavors in the mix. Gauc is full of healthy fats, too, so go ahead and nosh on this with your favorite vegetables for a boost of fiber. 
(Find the full recipe here .) 5/10 Shutterstock & Crème de la Crumb/Tiffany Edwards CHICKEN ENCHILADA DIP 
This enchilada dip will satisfy your cravings for Mexican without the commitment of making an entire meal. It’s full of chicken and black beans, so you’ll still pack in protein, but it also includes a layer of cheese on top for gooey goodness. 
(Find the full recipe here .) 6/10 Shutterstock & Wonky Wonderful/Nicole Harris EASY CHEESY CHILI DIP 
This hearty dip is the the most comforting thing you can make on a cold night in, even while wild football fans scream at the TV. The cream cheese makes richer than your traditional bowl of chili, but it’s still stacked with beef and beans, which will help keep you satisfied. 
(Find the full recipe here .) 7/10 Shutterstock & Cake ‘N Knife/Meghan Bassett CRAB RANGOON DIP 
If you’re a fan of classic crab rangoons, transform the Chinese staple into a dip. You won’t have to fuss with trying to make individual wontons and it will taste just as good, if not better than the classic appetizer. 
(Find the full recipe here .) 8/10 Shutterstock & A Flavor Journal/Sara Alvord BUFFALO CHICKEN DIP 
The following dips are your traditional calorie bombs, but you can still indulge by scooping out a hand-sized portion if you want to avoid overeating. Plus, you can’t have football without buffalo chicken: Whether it’s wings, a wrap, a sandwich, you name it, we’d probably eat it if it had buffalo sauce on it. This dip is no exception. While it’s loaded with cheese, you’ll get a serving of chicken in there for some added protein. 
(Find the full recipe here .) 9/10 Shutterstock & Damn Delicious/Chungah Rhee CHEESY BACON SPINACH DIP 
Cheese? We’re listening. Bacon? We’re in. Nix your traditional queso and make your own this year. Don’t let the spinach fool you, though. This dip is still full of cheese, sour cream, mayo, and more cheese. You’ll want to eat the whole damn pan, so grab yourself a plate and dip with vegetables if you don’t want to overdo it. 
(Find the full recipe here .) 10/10 Shutterstock & Spend With Pennies/Holly Nilsson DUNKAROO DIP 
Want to make the Super Bowl feel like your birthday? Look no further than dunkaroo dip: This dessert is literally just a blend of funfetti cake mix, cool whip, and Greek yogurt. Healthy? It’s probably the least nutritious thing you can have on this list. Delicious and worth the extra calories? Absolutely.
